[src:differential-algebraic-equations/backward-differentiation-formula] The **backward differentiation formula** (**BDF**) is a family of implicit methods for the numerical integration of ordinary differential equations.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/backward-differentiation-formula] They are linear multistep methods that, for a given function and time, approximate the derivative of that function using information from already computed time points, thereby increasing the accuracy of the approximation.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/backward-differentiation-formula] These methods are especially used for the solution of stiff differential equations.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/backward-differentiation-formula] The methods were first introduced by Charles F.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/backward-differentiation-formula] William Gear in a seminal paper based on his earlier unpublished work.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/backward-differentiation-formula] where h denotes the step size and $t_{n}=t_{0}+nh$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/backward-differentiation-formula] Since f is evaluated for the unknown $y_{n+s}$ , BDF methods are implicit and possibly require the solution of nonlinear equations at each step.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/backward-differentiation-formula] The coefficients $a_{k}$ and $\beta$ are chosen so that the method achieves order s , which is the maximum possible.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/backward-differentiation-formula] Using that $t_{n}=t_{0}+nh$ and multiplying by h one arrives at the BDF method of order s .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/backward-differentiation-formula] Methods with *s* > 6 are not zero-stable so they cannot be used.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/backward-differentiation-formula] The stability of numerical methods for solving stiff equations is indicated by their region of absolute stability.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/backward-differentiation-formula] For the BDF methods, these regions are shown in the plots below.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/backward-differentiation-formula] Ideally, the region contains the left half of the complex plane, in which case the method is said to be A-stable.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/backward-differentiation-formula] However, linear multistep methods with an order greater than 2 cannot be A-stable.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/backward-differentiation-formula] The stability region of the higher-order BDF methods contain a large part of the left half-plane and in particular the whole of the negative real axis.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/backward-differentiation-formula] The BDF methods are the most efficient linear multistep methods of this kind.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] In computational chemistry, a **constraint algorithm** is a method for satisfying the Newtonian motion of a rigid body which consists of mass points.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] A restraint algorithm is used to ensure that the distance between mass points is maintained.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The general steps involved are: (i) choose novel unconstrained coordinates (internal coordinates), (ii) introduce explicit constraint forces, (iii) minimize constraint forces implicitly by the technique of Lagrange multipliers or projection methods.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Constraint algorithms are often applied to molecular dynamics simulations.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Although such simulations are sometimes performed using internal coordinates that automatically satisfy the bond-length, bond-angle and torsion-angle constraints, simulations may also be performed using explicit or implicit constraint forces for these three constraints.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] However, explicit constraint forces give rise to inefficiency; more computational power is required to get a trajectory of a given length.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Therefore, internal coordinates and implicit-force constraint solvers are generally preferred.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Constraint algorithms achieve computational efficiency by neglecting motion along some degrees of freedom.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] For instance, in atomistic molecular dynamics, typically the length of covalent bonds to hydrogen are constrained; however, constraint algorithms should not be used if vibrations along these degrees of freedom are important for the phenomenon being studied.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] where **M** is a *mass matrix* and **q** is the vector of generalized coordinates that describe the particles' positions.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] For example, the vector **q** may be a *3N* Cartesian coordinates of the particle positions **r***k*, where *k* runs from 1 to *N*; in the absence of constraints, **M** would be the *3N*x*3N* diagonal square matrix of the particle masses.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The vector **f** represents the generalized forces and the scalar *V*(**q**) represents the potential energy, both of which are functions of the generalized coordinates **q**.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] For brevity, these functions *g**i* are grouped into an *M*-dimensional vector **g** below.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The task is to solve the combined set of differential-algebraic (DAE) equations, instead of just the ordinary differential equations (ODE) of Newton's second law.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] This problem was studied in detail by Joseph Louis Lagrange, who laid out most of the methods for solving it.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The simplest approach is to define new generalized coordinates that are unconstrained; this approach eliminates the algebraic equations and reduces the problem once again to solving an ordinary differential equation.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The drawback of this approach is that the equations may become unwieldy and complex; for example, the mass matrix **M** may become non-diagonal and depend on the generalized coordinates.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] A second approach is to introduce explicit forces that work to maintain the constraint; for example, one could introduce strong spring forces that enforce the distances among mass points within a "rigid" body.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The two difficulties of this approach are that the constraints are not satisfied exactly, and the strong forces may require very short time-steps, making simulations inefficient computationally.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] A third approach is to use a method such as Lagrange multipliers or projection to the constraint manifold to determine the coordinate adjustments necessary to satisfy the constraints.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Finally, there are various hybrid approaches in which different sets of constraints are satisfied by different methods, e.g., internal coordinates, explicit forces and implicit-force solutions.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The simplest approach to satisfying constraints in energy minimization and molecular dynamics is to represent the mechanical system in so-called *internal coordinates* corresponding to unconstrained independent degrees of freedom of the system.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] For example, the dihedral angles of a protein are an independent set of coordinates that specify the positions of all the atoms without requiring any constraints.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The difficulty of such internal-coordinate approaches is twofold: the Newtonian equations of motion become much more complex and the internal coordinates may be difficult to define for cyclic systems of constraints, e.g., in ring puckering or when a protein has a disulfide bond.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The original methods for efficient recursive energy minimization in internal coordinates were developed by Gō and coworkers.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Efficient recursive, internal-coordinate constraint solvers were extended to molecular dynamics.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Analogous methods were applied later to other systems.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] In most of molecular dynamics simulations that use constraint algorithms, constraints are enforced using the method of Lagrange multipliers.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] where $\scriptstyle \mathbf {x} _{k\alpha }(t)$ and $\scriptstyle \mathbf {x} _{k\beta }(t)$ are the positions of the two particles involved in the *k*th constraint at the time *t* and $d_{k}$ is the prescribed inter-particle distance.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Adding the constraint forces does not change the total energy, as the net work done by the constraint forces (taken over the set of particles that the constraints act on) is zero.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Note that the sign on $\lambda _{k}$ is arbitrary and some references have an opposite sign.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] where ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{i}(t+\Delta t)$ is the unconstrained (or uncorrected) position of the *i*th particle after integrating the unconstrained equations of motion.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] simultaneously for the n unknown Lagrange multipliers $\lambda _{k}$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Since not all particles contribute to all of constraints, $\mathbf {J} _{\sigma }$ is a block matrix and can be solved individually to block-unit of the matrix.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] In other words, $\mathbf {J} _{\sigma }$ can be solved individually for each molecule.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Instead of constantly updating the vector ${\underline {\lambda }}$ , the iteration can be started with ${\underline {\lambda }}^{(0)}=\mathbf {0}$ , resulting in simpler expressions for $\sigma _{k}(t)$ and ${\frac {\partial \sigma _{k}(t)}{\partial \lambda _{j}}}$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The above procedure is repeated until the solution of constraint equations, $\sigma _{k}(t+\Delta t)$ , converges to a prescribed tolerance of a numerical error.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Although there are a number of algorithms to compute the Lagrange multipliers, these difference is rely only on the methods to solve the system of equations.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] For this methods, quasi-Newton methods are commonly used.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The SETTLE algorithm solves the system of non-linear equations analytically for $n=3$ constraints in constant time.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Although it does not scale to larger numbers of constraints, it is very often used to constrain rigid water molecules, which are present in almost all biological simulations and are usually modelled using three constraints (e.g.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The SHAKE algorithm was first developed for satisfying a bond geometry constraint during molecular dynamics simulations.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The method was then generalised to handle any holonomic constraint, such as those required to maintain constant bond angles, or molecular rigidity.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] This amounts to assuming that $\mathbf {J} _{\sigma }$ is diagonally dominant and solving the k th equation only for the k unknown.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] for all $k=1\ldots n$ iteratively until the constraint equations $\sigma _{k}(t+\Delta t)$ are solved to a given tolerance.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The calculation cost of each iteration is ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ , and the iterations themselves converge linearly.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] A noniterative form of SHAKE was developed later on.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Several variants of the SHAKE algorithm exist.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Although they differ in how they compute or apply the constraints themselves, the constraints are still modelled using Lagrange multipliers which are computed using the Gauss–Seidel method.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The original SHAKE algorithm is capable of constraining both rigid and flexible molecules (e.g. water, benzene and biphenyl) and introduces negligible error or energy drift into a molecular dynamics simulation.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] One issue with SHAKE is that the number of iterations required to reach a certain level of convergence does rise as molecular geometry becomes more complex.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] To reach 64 bit computer accuracy (a relative tolerance of $\approx 10^{-16}$ ) in a typical molecular dynamics simulation at a temperature of 310K, a 3-site water model having 3 constraints to maintain molecular geometry requires an average of 9 iterations (which is 3 per site per time-step).
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] A 4-site butane model with 5 constraints needs 17 iterations (22 per site), a 6-site benzene model with 12 constraints needs 36 iterations (72 per site), while a 12-site biphenyl model with 29 constraints requires 92 iterations (229 per site per time-step).
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Hence the CPU requirements of the SHAKE algorithm can become significant, particularly if a molecular model has a high degree of rigidity.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] A later extension of the method, QSHAKE (Quaternion SHAKE) was developed as a faster alternative for molecules composed of rigid units, but it is not as general purpose.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] It works satisfactorily for *rigid* loops such as aromatic ring systems but QSHAKE fails for flexible loops, such as when a protein has a disulfide bond.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Further extensions include RATTLE, WIGGLE, and MSHAKE.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] While RATTLE works the same way as SHAKE, yet using the Velocity Verlet time integration scheme, WIGGLE extends SHAKE and RATTLE by using an initial estimate for the Lagrange multipliers $\lambda _{k}$ based on the particle velocities.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] It is worth mentioning that MSHAKE computes corrections on the constraint *forces*, achieving better convergence.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] A final modification to the SHAKE algorithm is the P-SHAKE algorithm that is applied to very rigid or semi-rigid molecules.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] P-SHAKE computes and updates a pre-conditioner which is applied to the constraint gradients before the SHAKE iteration, causing the Jacobian $\mathbf {J} _{\sigma }$ to become diagonal or strongly diagonally dominant.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The thus de-coupled constraints converge much faster (quadratically as opposed to linearly) at a cost of ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The M-SHAKE algorithm solves the non-linear system of equations using Newton's method directly.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] is solved exactly using an LU decomposition.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Each iteration costs ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ operations, yet the solution converges quadratically, requiring fewer iterations than SHAKE.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] This solution was first proposed in 1986 by Ciccotti and Ryckaert under the title "the matrix method", yet differed in the solution of the linear system of equations.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Ciccotti and Ryckaert suggest inverting the matrix $\mathbf {J} _{\sigma }$ directly, yet doing so only once, in the first iteration.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The first iteration then costs ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ operations, whereas the following iterations cost only ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ operations (for the matrix-vector multiplication).
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] This improvement comes at a cost though, since the Jacobian is no longer updated, convergence is only linear, albeit at a much faster rate than for the SHAKE algorithm.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Several variants of this approach based on sparse matrix techniques were studied by Barth *et al.*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] The SHAPE algorithm is a multicenter analog of SHAKE for constraining rigid bodies of three or more centers.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] This approach involves a single 3×3 matrix diagonalization followed by three or four rapid Newton iterations to determine the rotation matrix.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] SHAPE provides the identical trajectory that is provided with fully converged iterative SHAKE, yet it is found to be more efficient and more accurate than SHAKE when applied to systems involving three or more centers.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] It extends the ability of SHAKE like constraints to linear systems with three or more atoms, planar systems with four or more atoms, and to significantly larger rigid structures where SHAKE is intractable.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] It also allows rigid bodies to be linked with one or two common centers (e.g. peptide planes) by solving rigid body constraints iteratively in the same basic manner that SHAKE is used for atoms involving more than one SHAKE constraint.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] An alternative constraint method, LINCS (Linear Constraint Solver) was developed in 1997 by Hess, Bekker, Berendsen and Fraaije, and was based on the 1986 method of Edberg, Evans and Morriss (EEM), and a modification thereof by Baranyai and Evans (BE).
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] This approximation only works for matrices with eigenvalues smaller than 1, making the LINCS algorithm suitable only for molecules with low connectivity.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] LINCS has been reported to be 3–4 times faster than SHAKE.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] Hybrid methods have also been introduced in which the constraints are divided into two groups; the constraints of the first group are solved using internal coordinates whereas those of the second group are solved using constraint forces, e.g., by a Lagrange multiplier or projection method.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/constraint-computational-chemistry] This approach was pioneered by Lagrange, and result in *Lagrange equations of the mixed type*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] In mathematics, a **differential-algebraic system of equations** (**DAE**) is a system of equations that either contains differential equations and algebraic equations, or is equivalent to such a system.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] The set of the solutions of such a system is a *differential algebraic variety*, and corresponds to an ideal in a differential algebra of differential polynomials.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] where $x(t)$ is a vector of unknown functions and the overdot denotes the time derivative, i.e., ${\dot {x}}={\frac {dx}{dt}}$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] This distinction between ODEs and DAEs is made because DAEs have different characteristics and are generally more difficult to solve.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] A DAE system of this form is called *semi-explicit*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] Every solution of the second half *g* of the equation defines a unique direction for *x* via the first half *f* of the equations, while the direction for *y* is arbitrary.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] But not every point *(x,y,t)* is a solution of *g*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] The variables in *x* and the first half *f* of the equations get the attribute *differential*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] The solution of a DAE consists of two parts, first the search for consistent initial values and second the computation of a trajectory.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] To find consistent initial values it is often necessary to consider the derivatives of some of the component functions of the DAE.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] The highest order of a derivative that is necessary for this process is called the *differentiation index*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] The equations derived in computing the index and consistent initial values may also be of use in the computation of the trajectory.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] A semi-explicit DAE system can be converted to an implicit one by decreasing the differentiation index by one, and vice versa.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] The distinction of DAEs to ODEs becomes apparent if some of the dependent variables occur without their derivatives.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] where $\lambda$ is a Lagrange multiplier.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] The momentum variables *u* and *v* should be constrained by the law of conservation of energy and their direction should point along the circle.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] Neither condition is explicit in those equations.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] restricting the direction of motion to the tangent of the circle.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] and the derivative of that last identity simplifies to $L^{2}{\dot {\lambda }}-3gv=0$ which implies the conservation of energy since after integration the constant $E={\tfrac {3}{2}}gy-{\tfrac {1}{2}}L^{2}\lambda ={\frac {1}{2}}(u^{2}+v^{2})+gy$ is the sum of kinetic and potential energy.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] To obtain unique derivative values for all dependent variables the last equation was three times differentiated.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] This gives a differentiation index of 3, which is typical for constrained mechanical systems.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] Another set of similar equations may be obtained starting from $(y_{0},v_{0})$ and a sign for *x*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] DAEs also naturally occur in the modelling of circuits with non-linear devices.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] Modified nodal analysis employing DAEs is used for example in the ubiquitous SPICE family of numeric circuit simulators.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] Similarly, Fraunhofer's Analog Insydes Mathematica package can be used to derive DAEs from a netlist and then simplify or even solve the equations symbolically in some cases.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] It is worth noting that the index of a DAE (of a circuit) can be made arbitrarily high by cascading/coupling via capacitors operational amplifiers with positive feedback.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] The index-1 property requires that *g* is solvable for *y*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] Every sufficiently smooth DAE is almost everywhere reducible to this semi-explicit index-1 form.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] Two major problems in solving DAEs are *index reduction* and *consistent initial conditions*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] It is a non-trivial task to convert arbitrary DAE systems into ODEs for solution by pure ODE solvers.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] Techniques which can be employed include *Pantelides algorithm* and *dummy derivative index reduction method*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] Alternatively, a direct solution of high-index DAEs with inconsistent initial conditions is also possible.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] This solution approach involves a transformation of the derivative elements through *orthogonal collocation on finite elements* or *direct transcription* into algebraic expressions.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] Once the model has been converted to algebraic equation form, it is solvable by large-scale nonlinear programming solvers (see APMonitor).
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] Several measures of DAEs tractability in terms of numerical methods have developed, such as *differentiation index*, *perturbation index*, *tractability index*, *geometric index*, and the *Kronecker index*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] We use the $\Sigma$ -method to analyze a DAE.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] We construct for the DAE a signature matrix $\Sigma =(\sigma _{i,j})$ , where each row corresponds to each equation $f_{i}$ and each column corresponds to each variable $x_{j}$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/differential-algebraic-system-of-equations] The entry in position $(i,j)$ is $\sigma _{i,j}$ , which denotes the highest order of derivative to which $x_{j}$ occurs in $f_{i}$ , or $-\infty$ if $x_{j}$ does not occur in $f_{i}$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] In mathematics, an **implicit equation** is a relation of the form $R(x_{1},\dots ,x_{n})=0,$ where R is a function of several variables (often a polynomial).
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] An **implicit function** is a function that is defined by an implicit equation, that relates one of the variables, considered as the value of the function, with the others considered as the arguments.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] For example, the equation $x^{2}+y^{2}-1=0$ of the unit circle defines y as an implicit function of x, $y={\sqrt {1-x^{2}}}$ , assuming −1 ≤ *x* ≤ 1 and y is restricted to nonnegative values.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Some equations do not admit an explicit solution.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] The implicit function theorem provides conditions under which some kinds of implicit equations define implicit functions, namely those that are obtained by equating to zero multivariable functions that are continuously differentiable.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] A common type of implicit function is an inverse function.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Not all functions have a unique inverse function.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Defining *g*−1 as the inverse of g is an implicit definition.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] However, this is often not possible, or only by introducing a new notation (as in the product log example below).
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Intuitively, an inverse function is obtained from g by interchanging the roles of the dependent and independent variables.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] An **algebraic function** is a function that satisfies a polynomial equation whose coefficients are themselves polynomials.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] where the coefficients *ai*(*x*) are polynomial functions of x.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] This algebraic function can be written as the right side of the solution equation *y* = *f*(*x*).
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Written like this, f is a multi-valued implicit function.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Algebraic functions play an important role in mathematical analysis and algebraic geometry.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] But even without specifying this explicit solution, it is possible to refer to the implicit solution of the unit circle equation as *y* = *f*(*x*), where f is the multi-valued implicit function.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Nevertheless, one can still refer to the implicit solution *y* = *f*(*x*) involving the multi-valued implicit function f.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Not every equation *R*(*x*, *y*) = 0 implies a graph of a single-valued function, the circle equation being one prominent example.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Another example is an implicit function given by *x* − *C*(*y*) = 0 where C is a cubic polynomial having a "hump" in its graph.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Thus, for an implicit function to be a *true* (single-valued) function it might be necessary to use just part of the graph.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] An implicit function can sometimes be successfully defined as a true function only after "zooming in" on some part of the x-axis and "cutting away" some unwanted function branches.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Then an equation expressing y as an implicit function of the other variables can be written.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] The defining equation *R*(*x*, *y*) = 0 can also have other pathologies.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] For example, the equation *x* = 0 does not imply a function *f*(*x*) giving solutions for y at all; it is a vertical line.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] In order to avoid a problem like this, various constraints are frequently imposed on the allowable sorts of equations or on the domain.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] The implicit function theorem provides a uniform way of handling these sorts of pathologies.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] In calculus, implicit differentiation is a method for finding the derivative of a function that is defined by an equation rather than by an explicit formula.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] defines y as a function of x , at least locally, implicit differentiation treats y as a function $y(x)$ and differentiates both sides of the equation with respect to x .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] The method is an application of the chain rule.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Implicit differentiation is useful when solving explicitly for one variable is inconvenient, produces several branches, or is not possible in elementary terms.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] For example, the circle $x^{2}+y^{2}=1$ cannot be represented globally as the graph of a single function $y=f(x)$ , but its upper and lower arcs can each be differentiated implicitly.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] The method allows for the computation of the tangent line approximation to $y(x)$ , given only the function F and the point $(x_{0},y_{0})$ at which the approximation is made, so that no other knowledge of the functional dependence of y on x is needed.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Tangent approximations to surfaces and higher-dimensional manifolds given by an equation or system of equations can be found by similar methods.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Let *R*(*x*, *y*) be a differentiable function of two variables, and (*a*, *b*) be a pair of real numbers such that *R*(*a*, *b*) = 0.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] The condition ⁠∂*R*/∂*y*⁠ ≠ 0 means that (*a*, *b*) is a regular point of the implicit curve of implicit equation *R*(*x*, *y*) = 0 where the tangent is not vertical.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] In a less technical language, implicit functions exist and can be differentiated, if the curve has a non-vertical tangent.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Consider a relation of the form *R*(*x*1, …, *x**n*) = 0, where R is a multivariable polynomial.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] The set of the values of the variables that satisfy this relation is called an implicit curve if *n* = 2 and an **implicit surface** if *n* = 3.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] The implicit equations are the basis of algebraic geometry, whose basic subjects of study are the simultaneous solutions of several implicit equations whose left-hand sides are polynomials.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] These sets of simultaneous solutions are called affine algebraic sets.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] The solutions of differential equations generally appear expressed by an implicit function.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Similarly, sometimes the level set *R*(*L*, *K*) is an isoquant showing various combinations of utilized quantities L of labor and K of physical capital each of which would result in the production of the same given quantity of output of some good.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] In this case the absolute value of the implicit derivative ⁠*dK*/*dL*⁠ is interpreted as the marginal rate of technical substitution between the two factors of production: how much more capital the firm must use to produce the same amount of output with one less unit of labor.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Often in economic theory, some function such as a utility function or a profit function is to be maximized with respect to a choice vector x even though the objective function has not been restricted to any specific functional form.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] The implicit function theorem guarantees that the first-order conditions of the optimization define an implicit function for each element of the optimal vector *x** of the choice vector x.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] When profit is being maximized, typically the resulting implicit functions are the labor demand function and the supply functions of various goods.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] When utility is being maximized, typically the resulting implicit functions are the labor supply function and the demand functions for various goods.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/implicit-function] Moreover, the influence of the problem's parameters on *x** — the partial derivatives of the implicit function — can be expressed as total derivatives of the system of first-order conditions found using total differentiation.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/method-of-lines] The **method of lines** (MOL, NMOL, NUMOL) is a technique for solving partial differential equations (PDEs) in which all but one dimension is discretized.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/method-of-lines] By reducing a PDE to a single continuous dimension, the method of lines allows solutions to be computed via methods and software developed for the numerical integration of ordinary differential equations (ODEs) and differential-algebraic systems of equations (DAEs).
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/method-of-lines] Many integration routines have been developed over the years in many different programming languages, and some have been published as open source resources.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/method-of-lines] The method of lines most often refers to the construction or analysis of numerical methods for partial differential equations that proceeds by first discretizing the spatial derivatives only and leaving the time variable continuous.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/method-of-lines] This leads to a system of ordinary differential equations to which a numerical method for initial value ordinary equations can be applied.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/method-of-lines] The method of lines in this context dates back to at least the early 1960s.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/method-of-lines] Many papers discussing the accuracy and stability of the method of lines for various types of partial differential equations have appeared since.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/method-of-lines] MOL requires that the PDE problem is well-posed as an initial value (Cauchy) problem in at least one dimension, because ODE and DAE integrators are initial value problem (IVP) solvers.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/method-of-lines] Thus it cannot be used directly on purely elliptic partial differential equations, such as Laplace's equation.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/method-of-lines] However, MOL has been used to solve Laplace's equation by using the *method of false transients*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/method-of-lines] In this method, a time derivative of the dependent variable is added to Laplace’s equation.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/method-of-lines] Finite differences are then used to approximate the spatial derivatives, and the resulting system of equations is solved by MOL.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/method-of-lines] It is also possible to solve elliptical problems by a *semi-analytical method of lines*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/method-of-lines] In this method, the discretization process results in a set of ODE's that are solved by exploiting properties of the associated exponential matrix.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/method-of-lines] Recently, to overcome the stability issues associated with the method of false transients, a perturbation approach was proposed which was found to be more robust than standard method of false transients for a wide range of elliptic PDEs.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] In numerical analysis, the **Runge–Kutta methods** (English: /ˈrʊŋəˈkʊtɑː/ ⓘ *RUUNG-ə-KUUT-tah*) are a family of implicit and explicit iterative methods, which include the Euler method, used in temporal discretization for the approximate solutions of simultaneous nonlinear equations.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] These methods were developed around 1900 by the German mathematicians Carl Runge and Wilhelm Kutta.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The most widely known member of the Runge–Kutta family is generally referred to as "RK4", the "classic Runge–Kutta method" or simply as "the Runge–Kutta method".
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Here y is an unknown function (scalar or vector) of time t , which we would like to approximate; we are told that ${\frac {dy}{dt}}$ , the rate at which y changes, is a function of t and of y itself.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] At the initial time $t_{0}$ the corresponding y value is $y_{0}$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The function f and the initial conditions $t_{0}$ , $y_{0}$ are given.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] In averaging the four slopes, greater weight is given to the slopes at the midpoint.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] If f is independent of y , so that the differential equation is equivalent to a simple integral, then RK4 is Simpson's rule.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The RK4 method is a fourth-order method, meaning that the local truncation error is on the order of $O(h^{5})$ , while the total accumulated error is on the order of $O(h^{4})$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] In many practical applications the function f is independent of t (so called autonomous system, or time-invariant system, especially in physics), and their increments are not computed at all and not passed to function f , with only the final formula for $t_{n+1}$ used.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The family of explicit Runge–Kutta methods is a generalization of the RK4 method mentioned above.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Note: the above equations may have different but equivalent definitions in some texts.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] To specify a particular method, one needs to provide the integer *s* (the number of stages), and the coefficients *aij* (for 1 ≤ *j* < *i* ≤ *s*), *bi* (for *i* = 1, 2, ..., *s*) and *ci* (for *i* = 2, 3, ..., *s*).
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The matrix [*aij*] is called the *Runge–Kutta matrix*, while the *bi* and *ci* are known as the *weights* and the *nodes*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] These data are usually arranged in a mnemonic device, known as a *Butcher tableau* (after John C.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] There are also accompanying requirements if one requires the method to have a certain order *p*, meaning that the local truncation error is O(*hp*+1).
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] These can be derived from the definition of the truncation error itself.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] This condition alone, however, is neither sufficient, nor necessary for consistency.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] In general, if an explicit s -stage Runge–Kutta method has order p , then it can be proven that the number of stages must satisfy $s\geq p$ and if $p\geq 5$ , then $s\geq p+1$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] However, it is not known whether these bounds are *sharp* in all cases.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] In some cases, it is proven that the bound cannot be achieved.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] For instance, Butcher proved that for $p>6$ , there is no explicit method with $s=p+1$ stages.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Butcher also proved that for $p>7$ , there is no explicit Runge-Kutta method with $p+2$ stages.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] In general, however, it remains an open problem what the precise minimum number of stages s is for an explicit Runge–Kutta method to have order p .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The provable bound above then implies that we cannot find methods of orders $p=1,2,\ldots ,6$ that require fewer stages than the methods we already know for these orders.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The work of Butcher also proves that 7th and 8th order methods have a minimum of 9 and 11 stages, respectively.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] An example of an explicit method of order 6 with 7 stages can be found in Ref.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Explicit methods of order 7 with 9 stages and explicit methods of order 8 with 11 stages are also known.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] A slight variation of "the" Runge–Kutta method is also due to Kutta in 1901 and is called the 3/8-rule.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The primary advantage this method has is that almost all of the error coefficients are smaller than in the popular method, but it requires slightly more floating-point operations per time step.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] However, the simplest Runge–Kutta method is the (forward) Euler method, given by the formula $y_{n+1}=y_{n}+hf(t_{n},y_{n})$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] This is the only consistent explicit Runge–Kutta method with one stage.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] In this family, $\alpha ={\tfrac {1}{2}}$ gives the midpoint method, $\alpha =1$ is Heun's method, and $\alpha ={\tfrac {2}{3}}$ is Ralston's method.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] As an example, consider the two-stage second-order Runge–Kutta method with α = 2/3, also known as Ralston method.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] with step size *h* = 0.025, so the method needs to take four steps.
