[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Explicit Runge–Kutta methods are generally unsuitable for the solution of stiff equations because their region of absolute stability is small; in particular, it is bounded.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] This issue is especially important in the solution of partial differential equations.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The instability of explicit Runge–Kutta methods motivates the development of implicit methods.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The difference with an explicit method is that in an explicit method, the sum over *j* only goes up to *i* − 1.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] This also shows up in the Butcher tableau: the coefficient matrix $a_{ij}$ of an explicit method is lower triangular.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The consequence of this difference is that at every step, a system of algebraic equations has to be solved.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] This increases the computational cost considerably.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] If a method with *s* stages is used to solve a differential equation with *m* components, then the system of algebraic equations has *ms* components.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] which can be re-arranged to get the formula for the backward Euler method listed above.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Another example for an implicit Runge–Kutta method is the trapezoidal rule.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The trapezoidal rule is a collocation method (as discussed in that article).
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] All collocation methods are implicit Runge–Kutta methods, but not all implicit Runge–Kutta methods are collocation methods.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The Gauss–Legendre methods form a family of collocation methods based on Gauss quadrature.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] A Gauss–Legendre method with *s* stages has order 2*s* (thus, methods with arbitrarily high order can be constructed).
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The advantage of implicit Runge–Kutta methods over explicit ones is their greater stability, especially when applied to stiff equations.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Consider the linear test equation $y'=\lambda y$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] where *e* stands for the vector of ones.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The function *r* is called the *stability function*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] It follows from the formula that *r* is the quotient of two polynomials of degree *s* if the method has *s* stages.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Explicit methods have a strictly lower triangular matrix *A*, which implies that det(*I* − *zA*) = 1 and that the stability function is a polynomial.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The numerical solution to the linear test equation decays to zero if | *r*(*z*) | < 1 with *z* = *h*λ.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The set of such *z* is called the *domain of absolute stability*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] In particular, the method is said to be absolute stable if all *z* with Re(*z*) < 0 are in the domain of absolute stability.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The stability function of an explicit Runge–Kutta method is a polynomial, so explicit Runge–Kutta methods can never be A-stable.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] If the method has order *p*, then the stability function satisfies $r(z)={\textrm {e}}^{z}+O(z^{p+1})$ as $z\to 0$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Thus, it is of interest to study quotients of polynomials of given degrees that approximate the exponential function the best.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] A Padé approximant with numerator of degree *m* and denominator of degree *n* is A-stable if and only if *m* ≤ *n* ≤ *m* + 2.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The Gauss–Legendre method with *s* stages has order 2*s*, so its stability function is the Padé approximant with *m* = *n* = *s*.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] This shows that A-stable Runge–Kutta can have arbitrarily high order.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] In contrast, the order of A-stable linear multistep methods cannot exceed two.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Adaptive methods are designed to produce an estimate of the local truncation error of a single Runge–Kutta step.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] This is done by having two methods, one with order p and one with order $p-1$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] These methods are interwoven, i.e., they have common intermediate steps.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Thanks to this, estimating the error has little or negligible computational cost compared to a step with the higher-order method.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] During the integration, the step size is adapted such that the estimated error stays below a user-defined threshold: If the error is too high, a step is repeated with a lower step size; if the error is much smaller, the step size is increased to save time.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] This results in an (almost), optimal step size, which saves computation time.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Moreover, the user does not have to spend time on finding an appropriate step size.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] where $k_{i}$ are the same as for the higher-order method.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The Runge–Kutta–Fehlberg method has two methods of orders 5 and 4.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] However, the simplest adaptive Runge–Kutta method involves combining Heun's method, which is order 2, with the Euler method, which is order 1.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Other adaptive Runge–Kutta methods are the Bogacki–Shampine method (orders 3 and 2), the Cash–Karp method and the Dormand–Prince method (both with orders 5 and 4).
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] A Runge–Kutta method is said to be *nonconfluent* if all the $c_{i},\,i=1,2,\ldots ,s$ are distinct.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] There are two derivatives two approximates, a Runge-Kutta-Nyström methods hence uses two Runge-Kutta matrices $a_{ij},a'_{ij}$ , and two sets of weights $b_{i},b'_{i}$ , but still only needs one set of nodes $c_{i}$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Assume the approximations have been carried out up to $t_{n}$ , with $y_{n}$ the approximation of $y(t_{n})$ and $y'_{n}$ the approximation of ${\frac {dy}{dt}}(t_{n})$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Where $g_{i},g'_{i}$ are the intermediate approximations of y and ${\frac {dy}{dt}}$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] It is strictly equivalent to work with the values $k_{j}=f(t_{n}+c_{j}h,g'_{j},g_{j})$ where the $g_{j},g'_{j}$ have been replaced with their formula, instead of working with $g_{i},g'_{i}$ , similarly to what we previously did with Runge-Kutta methods, but the system is easier to write this way.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] A Runge-Kutta-Nyström method is said to be explicit if both $A,A'$ are strictly lower triangular, and in this case, the sums ${\textstyle \sum _{j=1}^{s}}$ in the expressions of $g_{i},g'_{i}$ , may be replaced with ${\textstyle \sum _{j=1}^{i-1}}$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Additionally, a Runge-Kutta-Nyström method is said to be of order p if the local truncation error of both $y_{n+1},y'_{n+1}$ is $O(h^{p+1})$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] This special case is particularly interesting since it allows for greater order than what a Runge-Kutta-Nyström can achieve in general.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The *A-stability* concept for the solution of differential equations is related to the linear autonomous equation $y'=\lambda y$ .
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] Dahlquist (1963) proposed the investigation of stability of numerical schemes when applied to nonlinear systems that satisfy a monotonicity condition.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] The corresponding concepts were defined as *G-stability* for multistep methods (and the related one-leg methods) and *B-stability* (Butcher, 1975) for Runge–Kutta methods.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] A Runge–Kutta method applied to the non-linear system $y'=f(y)$ , which verifies $\langle f(y)-f(z),\ y-z\rangle \leq 0$ , is called *B-stable*, if this condition implies $\|y_{n+1}-z_{n+1}\|\leq \|y_{n}-z_{n}\|$ for two numerical solutions.
[src:differential-algebraic-equations/runge-kutta-methods] A sufficient condition for *B-stability* is: B and Q are non-negative definite.
